<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="s_primitive_roots" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Primitive roots</title>
    <objectives>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Develop some theory about polynomials with coefficients in one of our familiar rings (<eg/>, <m>\Z</m>, <m>\Z/n\Z</m>, <m>\Q</m>, <m>\R</m>).
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Prove that <m>(\Z/p\Z)^*</m> has a primitive root for <m>p</m> prime. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Derive counting formulas for elements of given order <m>k</m> in <m>(\Z/n\Z)^*</m>, assuming that a primitive root exists. 
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </objectives>
    <subsection xml:id="ss_prim_roots_intro">
    <title>Introduction</title>
    
    
    <p>
        In this section we will show that <m>(\Z/p\Z)^*</m> has a primitive root for <m>p</m> prime. Before getting to that existential statement, we first prove a <em>conditional</em> result that counts the number of primitive roots modulo <m>n</m>, assuming one exists. Note that <xref ref="th_primitive_roots"/> provides an unconditional version of this result in the special case where <m>n=p</m> is a prime integer. 
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="th_number_of_primitive_roots">
        <title>Number of primitive roots</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>n</m> be a positive integer. 
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            If <m>(\Z/n\Z)^*</m> has a primitive root, then it has exactly <m>\phi(\phi(n))</m> distinct primitive roots. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            More generally, if <m>(\Z/n\Z)^*</m> has a primitive root, then for each positive divisor <m>d</m> of <m>\phi(n)</m>, the number of elements of <m>(\Z/n\Z)^*</m> of order <m>d</m> is <m>\phi(d)</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
            <p>
                Assume <m>r</m> is a primitive root of <m>(\Z/n\Z)^*</m>, so that 
                <md>
                    <mrow>(\Z/n\Z)^* \amp = \{1,r,r^2,\dots, r^{\phi(n)-1}\}</mrow>
                </md>.
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            If <m>s</m> is a primitive root of <m>(\Z/n\Z)^*</m>, then <m>s=r^i</m> for some <m>i\in \{0,1,\dots, \phi(n)-1\}</m>. And furthermore, since <m>\ord s=\phi(n)</m>, we must have 
                <md>
                    <mrow>\phi(n) \amp =\ord s</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \ord r^i</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \phi(n)/\gcd(i,\phi(n))</mrow>
                </md>,
                by <xref ref="prop_order_mod_n"/>. This happens if and only if <m>\gcd(i,\phi(n))=1</m>. Thus , the number of primitive roots of <m>(\Z/n\Z)^*</m> is equal in this case to the number of <m>i\in \{0,1,\dots, \phi(n)-1\}</m> satisfying <m>\gcd(i,\phi(n))=1</m>. This is <m>\phi(\phi(n))</m>, by definition. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            This result is very easy to prove if you know a little group theory, and a little tricky to prove (for general <m>n</m>) using just elementary number theory. We will defer the proof to a <em>guided</em> homework exercise.   
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </proof>
    </theorem>
    <example xml:id="eg_primitive_roots_25">
    <title>Primitive roots modulo 25</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    We saw in <xref ref="eg_primitive_roots"/> that <m>(\Z/25\Z)^*</m> has a primitive root, and that in fact <m>2, 3, 8, 12, 13,17, 22, 23</m> are all of the primitive roots of <m>(\Z/25\Z)^*</m>. Observe that there are exactly <m>8</m> of these; and sure enough, we have 
    <md>
        <mrow>\phi(\phi(25)) \amp =\phi(20)</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = \phi(4)\phi(5)</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = 2\cdot 4=8</mrow>
    </md>.
    </p>
    </statement>
    </example>
    
    <p>
        We now make a small digression to develop some notions about polynomials with coefficients in a given number system. We could develop this theory for polynomials with coefficients in an arbitrary ring <m>R</m>, but since we have not given an official definition of a ring, we will restrict ourselves to the case where our coefficients lie in <m>\Z</m>, <m>\Q</m>, <m>\R</m>, or <m>\Z/n\Z</m> for some positive integer <m>n</m>.
    </p>
    </subsection>
    <subsection xml:id="ss_prim_roots_polys">
    <title>Polynomials with coefficients in rings</title>
    
    
    <definition xml:id="d_polynomials">
    <title>Polynomials over a ring</title>
    <notation>
        <usage><m>R[x]</m></usage>
      <description>set of polynomials with coeffiecients in <m>R</m></description>
    </notation>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>R</m> be either <m>\Z</m>, <m>\Q</m>, <m>\R</m>, or <m>\Z/n\Z</m> for some positive integer <m>n</m>. A <term>polynomial over <m>R</m> in the indeterminate (or variable) <m>x</m></term> is a formal expression of the form 
<md>
    <mrow>f(x) \amp =a_nx^n+a_{n-1}x^{n-1}+\cdots a_1x+a_0</mrow>
</md>,
where <m>n</m> is a nonnegative integer and <m>a_i\in R</m> for all <m>0\leq i\leq n</m>. We call <m>a_i</m> the <term>coefficients</term> of <m>f</m>, and we denote by <m>R[x]</m> the set of all polynomials with coefficients in <m>R</m>: <ie/>, 
<md number="yes">
    <mrow xml:id="eq_poly_over_R">R[x] \amp =\{\anpoly\mid n\in \Z_{\geq 0}, a_i\in R\}</mrow>
</md>.
 The polynomial is <term>nonzero</term> if <m>a_i\ne 0</m> for some <m>i</m>, and <term>zero</term> otherwise. The <term>degree</term> of a nonzero polynomial <m>f</m>, denoted <m>\deg f</m>, is the largest positive integer <m>n</m> such that the <m>n</m>-th coefficient of <m>f</m> is nonzero. 
</p>
    <p>
         Two nonzero polynomial <m>f(x)=\anpoly</m> and <m>g(x)=\bmpoly</m> with <m>a_n\ne 0</m> and <m>b_m\ne 0</m> are equal, written <m>f=g</m> if <m>n=m</m> and <m>a_i=b_i</m> for all <m>0\leq i\leq n</m>. 
    </p>
    <p>
        Given a polynomial <m>f(x)=\anpoly</m> and an element <m>r\in F</m>, the <term>evaluation of <m>f</m> at <m>r</m></term> is the element <m>f(r)</m> defined as 
        <md number="yes">
            <mrow>f(r) \amp = a_nr^n+a_{n-1}r^{n-1}+\cdots a_1r+a_0 </mrow>
        </md>.
        In this manner, the polynomial <m>f</m> defines a function <m>f\colon R\rightarrow R</m>. An element <m>r\in F</m> is a <term>root</term> of <m>f</m> if <m>f(r)=0</m>. 
    </p>
    <p>
        Lastly, addition and multiplication of polynomials are defined as usual. In particular, given <m>f(x)=\anpoly</m> and <m>g(x)=\bmpoly</m>, we have 
        <md number="yes">
            <mrow xml:id="eq_poly_mult">f(x)g(x) \amp =c_{n+m}x^{n+m}+\cdots +c_1x+c_0</mrow>
        </md>,
            where 
            <md number="yes">
                <mrow xml:id="eq_poly_mult_coeff">c_k \amp =\sum_{i=0}^ka_ib_{k-i}</mrow>
            </md>
            for all <m>0\leq k\leq n+m</m>.
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    
       
    <p>
        Although we stated our definitions for polynomials over general rings, for the next theorem we need to restrict ourselves to the case where the coefficients lie in a field. Again, since we have not given a definition of a field, we will state the results for polynomials with coeffiecients in <m>\Q</m>, <m>\R</m>, or <m>\F_p</m> for some prime integer <m>p</m>.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="th_polynomials_props">
    <title>Polynomial properties</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>F</m> be either <m>\Q</m>, <m>\R</m>, or <m>\F_p</m> for some prime integer <m>p</m>,  and let <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> be nonzero polynomials over <m>F</m>. 
    <ol>
        <li>
            <title>Degree of products</title>
            
            
            <p>
                <m>\deg fg=\deg f+\deg g</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <title>Division with remainder</title>
            <p>
               There are unique polynomials <m>q</m> and <m>r</m> such that <m>f(x)=q(x)g(x)+r(x)</m> and either <m>r(x)=0</m> or <m>0\leq \deg r&lt; \deg g </m>.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <title>Roots and factorization</title>
            <p>
                An element <m>r\in F</m> is a root of <m>f</m> if and only if we have <m>f(x)=(x-r)g(x)</m> for some polynomial <m>g</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <title>Roots and degree</title>
            <p>
                Let <m>\deg f=n</m>. There are at most <m>n</m> distinct roots of <m>f</m> in <m>F</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
    <p>
        In the arguments below, besides the ring structure of <m>F</m>, we will use two crucial additional properties that are related to one another: 
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    If <m>r\in F</m> is nonzero, then there is an element <m>r^{-1}</m> such that <m>rr^{-1}=1</m>. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    If <m>r</m> and <m>s</m> are nonzero elements of <m>F</m>, then <m>rs</m> is nonzero. 
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
        The second property is actually a consequence of the first: assume <m>r</m> is nonzero; by the first property, there is an element <m>r^{-1}</m> satisfying <m>r^{-1}r=1</m>; if <m>rs=0</m> for some element <m>s\in F</m>, then multiplying both sides by <m>r^{-1}</m>, we conclude that <m>s=0</m>; thus if <m>r</m> and <m>s</m> are nonzero, then <m>rs</m> is nonzero.
    </p>
    <p> Now for the proofs of the four statements. 
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Let <m>f(x)=\anpoly</m> and <m>g(x)=\bmpoly</m>, where <m>a_n\ne 0</m> and <m>b_m\ne 0</m>, so that <m>\deg f=n</m> and <m>\deg g=m</m>. We then have 
                
                    <md number="yes">
                        <mrow>f(x)g(x) \amp = a_nb_mx^{n+m}+\text{lower order terms}</mrow>
                    </md>.
                    Since <m>a_n</m> and <m>b_m</m> are nonzero, then <m>a_nb_m\ne 0</m> (See above.) It follows that <m>\deg fg=n+m=\deg f+\deg g</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    We omit a formal proof of this result, which is basically a consequence of the fact that for any of the given number systems <m>F</m> we can perform polynomial long division in the same manner as we do over <m>\R</m>. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    For any <m>r\in F</m>, using division with remainder, we can write <m>f</m> uniquely as 
                    <md>
                        <mrow>f(x) \amp =q(x)(x-r)+s(x)</mrow>
                    </md>
                    where either <m>s(x)=0</m> or <m>0\leq \deg s(x)&lt; \deg (x-r)=1</m>. In other words, we have <m>f(x)=q(x)(x-r)+c</m> for some constant <m>c\in F</m>. Since <m>f(r)=q(r)(r-r)+c=c</m>, we see that <m>r</m> is a root of <m>f</m> if and only if <m>c=0</m>, if and only if <m>f(x)=q(x)(x-r)</m>. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    We proceed by induction on <m>n=\deg f</m>. 
                </p>
                <p>
                    Base step: <m>n=0</m>. Since <m>\deg f=0</m> in this case, we have <m>f(x)=c</m> for some constant <m>c\in F</m>. Since <m>f</m> is assumed to be nonzero, we have <m>c\ne 0</m>. But then <m>f(r)=c\ne 0</m> for all <m>r\in F</m>, showing that <m>f</m> has zero roots. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Let <m>n\geq 0</m>, and assume the result holds for all nonzero polynomials of degree <m>n</m>. Let <m>f</m> be a polynomial of degree <m>n+1</m>. If <m>f</m> has no roots, then we are done. Otherwise, let <m>r\in F</m> be a root of <m>f</m>, and write <m>f(x)=(x-r)g(x)</m>. Since <m>n+1=\deg f=\deg(x-r)+\deg g(x)=1+\deg g(x)</m>, we see that <m>\deg g=n</m> (and in particular, <m>g</m> is nonzero). Suppose <m>s\ne r</m> is another root of <m>f</m>. Since <m>f(s)=(s-r)g(s)=0</m> and <m>s-r\ne 0</m>, we must have <m>g(s)=0</m>. (Again, see the first paragraph of this proof.) Thus any other root of <m>f</m> besides <m>r</m> is a root of <m>g</m>. Since <m>g</m> has degree <m>n</m>, it has at most <m>n</m> distinct roots by induction. We conclude that <m>f</m> has at most <m>n+1</m> distinct roots, as desired. 
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
    </proof>
    </theorem>
    </subsection>
    <subsection xml:id="ss_prim_roots_mod_p">
    <title>Primitive roots modulo a prime</title>
    
    
    <p>
        With this bit of polynomial theory under our belt, we move on to a proof that <m>(\Z/p\Z)^*</m> has a primitive root for <m>p</m> prime. We begin with two lemmas. The first is a classic identity involving the Euler totient function that is usually covered in the first quarter of the class. 
    </p>
     <lemma xml:id="lem_totient_identity">
        <title>Totient function identity</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>n</m> be a positive integer, and let <m>\phi</m> be the Euler totient function. 
                <md number="yes">
                    <mrow xml:id="eq_totient_identity">\sum_{d\mid n}\phi(d) \amp = n </mrow>
                </md>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </lemma>
    <lemma xml:id="lemma_order_k_bound">
        <title>Elements of order <m>k</m> bound</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>p</m> be a prime integer, and let <m>k</m> be a positive integer. The number of elements of <m>(\Z/p\Z)^*</m> of order <m>k</m> is either <m>0</m> or <m>\phi(k)</m>.  
            </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
            <p>
                If there are no elements of <m>(\Z/p\Z)^*</m> of order <m>k</m>, then we are done. Otherwise, let <m>r\in (\Z/p\Z)^*</m> have order <m>k</m>. It follows that each of the <m>k</m> elements 
                <m>x=r^i\in \angvec{r}</m> satisfies <m>x^k=1</m>, or equivalently <m>x^k-1=0</m>. Since the polynomial <m>f(x)=x^k-1</m> has coefficients in the field <m>\F_p=\Z/p\Z</m>, and has degree equal to <m>k</m>, <m>f</m> has at most <m>k</m> roots. We conclude that the roots of <m>f</m> are precisely the elements of <m>\angvec{r}</m>. In particular, any other element <m>s</m> of order <m>k</m> must be of the form <m>s=r^i</m> for some <m>i\in \{0,1,\dots, k-1\}</m>. Since <m>\ord r^i=k/\gcd(i,k)</m>, we see that <m>s=r^i</m> has order <m>k</m> if and only if <m>\gcd(i,k)=1</m>. We conclude that there are precisely <m>\phi(k)</m> elements of <m>(\Z/p\Z)^*</m> of order <m>k</m>. 
            </p>
        </proof>
    </lemma>
    <theorem xml:id="th_primitive_roots">
    <title>Primitive roots modulo <m>p</m></title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>p</m> be a prime integer. For each positive integer <m>k</m>, let <m>F_k</m> be the set of elements of <m>(\Z/p\Z)^*</m> of order <m>k</m>. 
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                If <m>k\nmid \phi(p)=p-1</m>, then <m>F_k=\emptyset</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                If <m>k\mid \phi(p)</m>, then <m>\abs{F_k}=\phi(k)</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                In particular, <m>\abs{F_{\phi(p)}}=\phi(p-1)\ne 0</m>, and thus there is a primitive root <m>r</m> of <m>\Z/p\Z</m>: <ie/>, there is an element <m>r\in (\Z/p\Z)^*</m> satisfying <m>\angvec{r}=(\Z/p\Z)^*</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
    <p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    We know from <xref ref="prop_order_mod_n"/> that <m>\ord r\mid \phi(p)</m> for all <m>p\in \F_p^*</m>. Thus, if <m>k\nmid \phi(p)</m>, then there is no element <m>r\in (\Z/p\Z)^*</m> of order <m>k</m>. Equivalently, <m>F_k=\emptyset</m> for all <m>k\nmid \phi(p)</m>. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    For each positive divisor <m>d</m> of <m>\phi(p)</m> we know from <xref ref="lemma_order_k_bound"/> that 
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\abs{F_d} \amp \in \{0,\phi(d)\}</mrow>
                    </md>.
                    In particular, we have <m>\abs{F_d}\leq \phi(d)</m> for all <m>d\mid \phi(p)</m>. Furthermore, since the sets <m>F_d</m> are disjoint (an element of <m>(\Z/p\Z)^*</m> has a unique order), and since <m>(\Z/p\Z)^*=\bigcup_{d\mid n}F_d</m> (every element of <m>(\Z/p\Z)^*</m> has order <m>d</m> for some divisor <m>d</m> of <m>\phi(p)</m>), we have
                    <md number="yes">
                        <mrow>p-1 \amp =\abs{\F_p^*}=\sum_{d\mid p-1}\abs{F_d} </mrow>
                    </md>.
                    From <xref ref="lem_totient_identity"/> we also know that 
                    <md>
                        <mrow>p-1 \amp = \sum_{d\mid p-1}\phi(d)</mrow>
                    </md>.
                    Subtracting these two equalities, we conclude that 
                    <md>
                        <mrow>0 \amp =\sum_{d\mid p-1}(\phi(d)-\abs{F_d})</mrow>
                    </md>.
                    Since <m>\abs{F_d}\leq \phi(d)</m> for all positive <m>d\mid p-1</m>, we conclude that <m>\phi(d)-\abs{F_d}\geq 0</m> for all positive <m>d\mid p-1</m>. But a sum of nonnegative numbers is zero if and only if each number is zero. Thus we conclude that 
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\abs{F_d} \amp = \phi(d)</mrow>
                    </md>
                    for all positive <m>d\mid p-1</m>. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    From (2), we conclude that <m>\ans{F_{p-1}}=\phi(p-1)</m>. Since <m>\phi(p-1)</m> is positive, we conclude that there is an element <m>r\in \F_p^*</m> of order <m>p-1</m>. (In fact there are precisely <m>\phi(p-1)</m> such elements.) Such an element satisfies <m>\angvec{r}=\F_p^*</m> and hence is a primitive root. 
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
    </proof>
    </theorem>
    <example xml:id="eg_prim_roots_">
    <title>Primitive roots modulo <m>17</m></title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>F_k</m> be the set of elements of <m>(\Z/17\Z)^*</m> of order <m>k</m>. 
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                Find a primitive root <m>r</m> of <m>(\Z/17\Z)^*</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                List all possible orders <m>k</m> of elements of <m>(\Z/17\Z)^*</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                For each possible order <m>k</m>, enumerate the elements of <m>F_k</m> described as powers of <m>r</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
</p>

    </statement>
    <solution>
    <p>
    
    </p>
    </solution>
    </example>
</subsection>
    <subsection xml:id="ss_sage_examples">
    <title>Sage examples</title>
    <project>
        <title>Primitive roots</title>
        <p>
            The Sage function <c>primitive_root(n)</c> returns a primitive root of <m>(\Z/n\Z)^*</m> if one exists, and raises an error otherwise. Furthermore, if <m>n=p</m> is prime, then <c>primitive_root(p)</c> returns the <em>smallest positive</em> integer <m>a</m> such that <m>[a]_p</m> is a primitive root of <m>(\Z/p\Z)^*</m>.
        </p>
        <sage>
            <input>
                for n in range(50):
                    try: 
                        print((n,primitive_root(n)))
                    except Exception as e:
                        print((n,e))
            </input>
            <output>
                
            </output>
        </sage>
    <p>
        
    </p>
    </project>

    <project xml:id="sage_unit_group">
        <title>Structure of unit group modulo <m>n</m></title>
    <p>
        Once we have created a modular ring <c>R=Integers(n)</c>, we can explore the structure of the unit group <m>R^*</m> using <c>G=R.unit_groups()</c>. 
    </p>
    <sage>
        <input>
            R=Integers(17)
            G=R.unit_group()
            G
        </input>
        <output>
            Multiplicative Abelian group isomorphic to C16
        </output>
    </sage>
    <p>
        Notice that the description of <m>G</m> is not precisely what we expected. Sage is describing <m>G</m> abstractly as a cyclic group of cardinality <m>16</m>. It has obscured the origins of this group as a subset of <m>R</m>. Let's see what the elements of <m>G</m> look like in Sage.
    </p>
    <sage>
        <input>
            [u for u in G]
        </input>
        <output>
            [1,
 f,
 f^2,
 f^3,
 f^4,
 f^5,
 f^6,
 f^7,
 f^8,
 f^9,
 f^10,
 f^11,
 f^12,
 f^13,
 f^14,
 f^15]
        </output>
    </sage>
    <p>
        It appears Sage has realized <m>G</m> as the cyclic group generated by an element it calls <m>f</m>. Sage has not actually forgotten the humble beginnings of <m>f</m>, as the method <c>f.value()</c> reveals. 
    </p>
    <sage>
        <input>
            [u.value() for u in G]
        </input>
        <output>
           [1, 3, 9, 10, 13, 5, 15, 11, 16, 14, 8, 7, 4, 12, 2, 6] 
        </output>
    </sage>
    <p>
        Aha! We now see that <m>f</m> corresponds to the element <m>3</m> in <m>R</m>. The Sage group object <m>G</m> has additional useful methods. For example, <m>G.subgroups()</m> produces a list of all subgroups of <m>G</m>, which in our language is the list of the distinct cyclic subgroups <m>\angvec{r}</m> as we let <m>r</m> vary over <m>(\Z/17\Z)^*</m>. 
    </p>
    <sage>
        <input>
            S=G.subgroups()
            S
        </input>
        <output>
            
        </output>
    </sage>
    <p>
       Note that once again, Sage describes these subgroups in terms of the element <m>f</m>. To reminder ourselves of what <m>f</m> is here, we can use the <c>.gen()</c> method, followed by the <c>.value()</c> method. For the list comprehension below, we need to exclude the trivial subgroup at the end. Do you see how we did this?
    </p>
    <sage>
        <input>
            [H.gen(0).value() for H in S if H.cardinality()>1]
        </input>
        <output>
            
        </output>
    </sage>
    </project>
    </subsection>
    
   
</section>